	</model>
	<model name="Central_Bank_Policies">
		<variables>
			<stock name="Insurance related\nCentral Bank\nDeposits" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<doc>It is the stock that records the cumulative scale of central bank insurance intervention over time. This “deposit” does not mean idle savings or a literal bank account balance; it represents how much the central bank has already injected through the insurance channel. The stock increases through insurance payout and safe interest earnings, so it accumulates both direct intervention and the interest earned on that accumulated position. This variable is included because the model needs to track the size and persistence of the central bank’s insurance-related balance-sheet exposure. The initial value is zero (no intervention).</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>initial_Bank_owned_Central_Bank_Deposit</eqn>
				<inflow>Central_Bank_insurance_payout</inflow>
				<inflow>deposit_earnings</inflow>
				<units>b$</units>
			</stock>
			<flow name="Central Bank\ninsurance payout" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<doc>It is the annual flow of funds the central bank provides to cover a share of climate-caused risky defaults. It exists because the model treats central bank insurance as an explicit policy mechanism that absorbs part of the climate-default burden which would otherwise remain in the private financial system. </doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF TIME &gt;= central_bank_insurance_policy_start_year THEN
total_climate_caused_risky_defaults * fraction_of_default_covered_central_bank_insurance
ELSE 0</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="deposit earnings">
				<doc>It is the annual return earned on the accumulated stock of insurance-related central bank deposits. It is included because once the central bank has built up this intervention position, the model assumes that position earns the safe interest rate rather than remaining inert. The equation is Central bank deposit × safe interest, so earnings increase when either the accumulated intervention stock becomes larger or the safe interest rate becomes higher. This variable matters because it gives the central bank insurance stock some endogenous financial dynamics and prevents it from behaving like a purely one-way accounting accumulation.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>Insurance_related_Central_Bank_Deposits*safe_interest</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</flow>
			<aux name="total climate caused\nrisky defaults" access="output" throughput="true" isee:autocreated="true">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="initial Bank owned Central Bank\nDeposit">
				<doc>It is the initial value of the insurance-related central bank deposit stock at the start of the simulation.This value is 0 b$, which means the model assumes there is no pre-existing central bank insurance intervention at time zero.</doc>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>b$</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="central bank insurance\npolicy start year" access="input">
				<eqn>2175</eqn>
				<units>year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="safe\ninterest" access="output" throughput="true" isee:autocreated="true">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="fraction of default covered central bank insurance" access="input">
				<eqn>0.4</eqn>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<flow name="Central Bank investment financing">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>central_bank_investment_1</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</flow>
			<aux name="central bank investment 1" access="output" throughput="true" isee:autocreated="true">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</aux>
			<flow name="Central Bank\ninterest payment" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>CB_firm_interest_payment</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</flow>
			<aux name="CB firm interest payment" access="input">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</aux>
			<stock name="Investment related\nCentral Bank\nDeposits" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<doc>In central bank insurance, the variable called “central bank deposit” is NOT a pile of money sitting somewhere.
It does not mean savings, reserves, or a bank account money collected earlier. Instead, in FRIDA it means “How big the central bank’s intervention has been so far.”</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>&quot;initial_Firm-owned_Central_Bank_Deposit&quot;</eqn>
				<inflow>Central_Bank_investment_financing</inflow>
				<inflow>investment_related_deposit_earning</inflow>
				<outflow>Central_Bank_interest_payment</outflow>
				<units>b$</units>
			</stock>
			<aux name="initial Firm-owned Central Bank\nDeposit">
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>b$</units>
			</aux>
			<flow name="increase in CB public\ninvestment fraction">
				<doc>For example, if “CB investments policy stance” is equal to 0,01, “CB investments policy” should increase by about 0,0025 after one year.

If real GDP growth last year was below the target, the policy should become more supportive this year.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF CB_investments_policy_stance &gt;=0
THEN CB_investments_policy_stance / increase_denominator_CB_investment_policy
ELSE 0</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="decrease in CB public\ninvestment fraction">
				<doc>For example, if “CB investments policy stance” is equal to -0,01, “CB investments policy” should decrease by about 0,00125 after one year.

If growth was above target, the policy can back off.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF CB_investments_policy_stance &lt; 0 AND Central_Bank_Public_Investments_fraction &gt; 0
THEN -CB_investments_policy_stance / decrease_denominator_CB_investment_policy
ELSE 0</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</flow>
			<stock name="Central Bank Public\nInvestments fraction" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<doc>This stock is the policy-controlled share of nominal GDP that the CB invests each year.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>initial_Central_Bank_Investments_Policy</eqn>
				<inflow>increase_in_CB_public_investment_fraction</inflow>
				<outflow>decrease_in_CB_public_investment_fraction</outflow>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</stock>
			<aux name="real GDP growth rate\nprevious years" access="output" throughput="true" isee:autocreated="true">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="CB investments policy stance">
				<doc>If the economy was weak last year (negative real GDP growth), the CB increases its investment stance.
If the economy was strong last year (positive real GDP growth), the CB reduces its investment stance.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>smoothed_real_GDP_rate - real_GDP_growth_rate_previous_years</eqn>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="initial Central Bank\nInvestments Policy">
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<group name="Central Bank Investment Policy" run="false">
				<format scale_by="auto"/>
				<entity name='"initial_Firm-owned_Central_Bank_Deposit"'/>
				<entity name="CB_firm_interest_payment"/>
				<entity name="CB_investments_policy_stance"/>
				<entity name="Central_Bank_interest_payment"/>
				<entity name="central_bank_investment_1"/>
				<entity name="Central_Bank_investment_financing"/>
				<entity name="central_bank_investment_policy_start_year"/>
				<entity name="central_bank_public_investment_payout"/>
				<entity name="Central_Bank_Public_Investments_fraction"/>
				<entity name="decrease_denominator_CB_investment_policy"/>
				<entity name="decrease_in_CB_public_investment_fraction"/>
				<entity name="GDP_rate_smooth_time"/>
				<entity name="increase_denominator_CB_investment_policy"/>
				<entity name="increase_in_CB_public_investment_fraction"/>
				<entity name="initial_Central_Bank_Investments_Policy"/>
				<entity name="Investment_related_Central_Bank_Deposits"/>
				<entity name="investment_related_deposit_earning"/>
				<entity name="Nominal_GDP"/>
				<entity name="real_GDP_growth_rate"/>
				<entity name="real_GDP_growth_rate_previous_years"/>
				<entity name="smoothed_real_GDP_rate"/>
			</group>
			<flow name="investment related\ndeposit earning">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>Investment_related_Central_Bank_Deposits*safe_interest</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</flow>
			<aux name="smoothed real GDP rate">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>SMTH1(real_GDP_growth_rate, GDP_rate_smooth_time[Run,Run])</eqn>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="real GDP growth rate" access="input">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>dmnl/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="GDP rate smooth time">
				<doc>${Assumption}
Smoothing horizon for real GDP growth used in the CB investment stance. This is a controller-smoothing parameter, not a policy target. Keep it long enough to filter cycle noise; 10–25 years is a defensible trend-growth window for a structural model.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>20</eqn>
				<format precision="1"/>
				<range min="10" max="30"/>
				<units>Year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="increase denominator\nCB investment policy">
				<doc>${Assumption}
It controls how quickly CB investment increases when GDP is below target.Smaller denominator = faster intervention.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>8</eqn>
				<format precision="1"/>
				<range min="4" max="12"/>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="decrease denominator\nCB investment policy">
				<doc>${Assumption}
Controls how quickly CB investment decreases when GDP is below target. It turns  parameter controlling how fast the policy backs off when growth is above target.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>8</eqn>
				<format precision="1"/>
				<range min="4" max="12"/>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<group name="Central Bank Insurance" run="false">
				<format scale_by="auto"/>
				<entity name="Central_Bank_insurance_payout"/>
				<entity name="central_bank_insurance_policy_start_year"/>
				<entity name="deposit_earnings"/>
				<entity name="fraction_of_default_covered_central_bank_insurance"/>
				<entity name="initial_Bank_owned_Central_Bank_Deposit"/>
				<entity name="Insurance_related_Central_Bank_Deposits"/>
				<entity name="safe_interest"/>
				<entity name="total_climate_caused_risky_defaults"/>
			</group>
			<aux name="central bank investment\npolicy start year" access="input">
				<eqn>2175</eqn>
				<units>year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="central bank\npublic investment payout" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>(IF TIME &gt;= central_bank_investment_policy_start_year
THEN Central_Bank_Public_Investments_fraction* Nominal_GDP
ELSE 0)</eqn>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="Nominal GDP" access="input">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</aux>
		</variables>
