	</model>
	<model name="Private_Insurance">
		<variables>
			<stock name="Insurance\nDeposits" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<doc>This represent the accumulated private insurance reserve pool that insurers build up in order to be able to pay claims when climate-related risky defaults occur. The model includes this stock because insurance must have a financial buffer; otherwise, payouts would appear exogenous and not constrained by the insurer’s own balance sheet. This insurance deposit increases with insurance premiums and insurance earnings, and decreases with private insurance payouts. The initial value is set to zero, which means the private insurance mechanism starts without pre-existing reserves and must build capacity endogenously once the policy becomes active</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<inflow>insurance_premiums</inflow>
				<inflow>insurance_earnings</inflow>
				<outflow>private_insurance_payouts</outflow>
				<units>b$</units>
			</stock>
			<flow name="insurance premiums">
				<doc>It is the inflow to insurance deposit each year. It exists because private insurance must be financed by agents in the economy and coverage cannot be provided for free. The equation says that after policy start year, premiums are calculated as normal investment × premium rate. This means premium collection scales with the amount of normal investment activity in the economy, so a larger investment base generates a larger premium base. Conceptually, the model treats premiums as the price paid for transferring climate-related default risk away from the banking system.
</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF TIME &gt;= insurance_policy_start_year THEN
normal_investment*insurance_premium_rate
ELSE 0</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</flow>
			<aux name="normal\ninvestment" access="input">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="insurance policy start year" access="input">
				<eqn>2030</eqn>
				<units>year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="average private debt interest" access="input">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</aux>
			<flow name="insurance earnings">
				<doc>It is the annual return earned on the insurance deposit. It is included because insurers do not only rely on premium inflows. Reserve funds are usually invested in relatively safe assets and generate income. 
The equation multiplies insurance deposit by private debt safe interest, meaning the larger the reserve base, or the higher the safe interest rate, the more the insurer earns each year. This helps prevent the reserve fund from being depleted too quickly. </doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>Insurance_Deposits*average_private_debt_interest</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="private\ninsurance payouts" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<doc>it is the annual flow of money paid out by insurers to cover climate-caused risky defaults. This will then decrease insurance deposit. Insurance mechanism only matters if it actually absorbs part of the losses that would otherwise remain on bank balance sheets. The equation means payouts rise automatically when climate-driven defaults rise, but only for the fraction that the insurance policy is designed to cover. So this variable operationalizes the  stabilizing role of the private insurance policy in the model.

</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF TIME &gt;= insurance_policy_start_year 
THEN
total_climate_caused_risky_defaults *fraction_of_default_covered_private_insurance
ELSE
0</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</flow>
			<aux name="total climate caused\nrisky defaults" access="input">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>b$/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="desired years of coverage">
				<doc>${Assumption}
It is the target or norm for how many years of coverage insurers would like to maintain. In this model the value is fixed at 4 years, meaning the insurer is assumed to be comfortable if reserves can finance roughly four years of payouts at the current claim rate. It anchors the premium-adjustment mechanism: premiums respond to whether actual coverage is above or below this desired level. 
</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>4</eqn>
				<format precision="0.1"/>
				<range min="1" max="6"/>
				<units>years</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="insurance premium rate">
				<doc>It is the effective premium rate applied to the investment base to calculate premium inflows. The model needs a pricing mechanism for insurance that can respond endogenously to risk conditions and reserve adequacy. 
It is shaped by: (1) normal insurance premium, which is baseline cost under normal climate risk, (2) minimum insurance premium, which is a lower bound so insurance never becomes unrealistically cheap, (3) effect of years of coverage on premiums, where longer coverage leads to higher premium due to uncertainty and climate risk can grow over-time.


</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>MIN(MAX(minimum_insurance_premium, normal_insurance_premium*effect_of_years_of_coverage_on_premiums), 1)</eqn>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="normal insurance premium">
				<doc>${Assumption}
It is the baseline premium rate under normal conditions.Its value is 0.005, meaning the baseline premium is 0.5% of normal investment once the policy is active. This parameter acts as the central pricing anchor from which actual premiums move up or down depending on coverage conditions. </doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>.005</eqn>
				<range min="0.002" max="0.02"/>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="actual years of coverage">
				<doc>It measures how long the current insurance reserve could continue paying claims if payouts remained at their current rate. The equation tells how many years of current payouts can be financed by the current reserve stock. A higher value means the insurer is better capitalized relative to ongoing claims, while a lower value means the reserve could be exhausted quickly. This variable is then used to influence premium pricing, so reserve adequacy feeds back into the cost of insurance.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>Insurance_Deposits//private_insurance_payouts</eqn>
				<units>year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="effect of years of coverage\non premiums">
				<doc>It translates reserve adequacy into a multiplier on premium pricing. It is to capture the idea that insurers adjust premiums depending on how comfortable or stressed they are about the duration of coverage they can support. The equation means the premium effect depends on the relative coverage ratio raised to a sensitivity exponent. Because this variable is a multiplier, it does not itself set the premium, but it changes the baseline premium upward or downward depending on the insurer’s reserve situation.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>MAX(1e-6, relative_years_of_coverage)^sensitivity_of_premiums_to_years_of_coverage</eqn>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="sensitivity of premiums\nto years of coverage">
				<doc>${Assumption}
It controls how strongly premium pricing reacts to the insurer’s relative coverage horizon. 
This parameter determines the steepness of the premium response rather than the premium level itself
The value is -1, so the premium effect is inversely related to relative years of coverage. That means when relative coverage is low, the effect on premiums rises. When relative coverage is high, the effect falls, which is consistent with the idea that tighter reserves make insurance more expensive. </doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>-1</eqn>
				<range min="-2" max="-0.2"/>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="relative years\nof coverage">
				<doc>It normalizes the insurer’s actual reserve position against its desired benchmark. It is included because premium setting should usually respond to a relative stress indicator rather than to an absolute number of years alone. A value of 1 means the insurer is exactly at its target coverage horizon. 
Values above 1 mean the reserve fund can cover claims for longer than the desired benchmark, while values below 1 indicate tighter reserve adequacy. </doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>actual_years_of_coverage/desired_years_of_coverage</eqn>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="minimum insurance premium">
				<doc>${Assumption}
Is the lower bound for the insurance premium rate. It is included so that insurance never becomes unrealistically cheap, even if reserve conditions would otherwise push the endogenous premium downward. 
Its value is 0.001, meaning the model imposes a minimum premium of 0.1% of the relevant investment base. </doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="Run"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>0.001</eqn>
				<range min="0.001" max="0.002"/>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="fraction of default covered private insurance" access="input">
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>dmnl</units>
			</aux>
		</variables>
